\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003ERoth spots\u003C/strong\u003E. Roth spots are retinal haemorrhages with pale centres, caused by rupture of retinal vessels and subsequent fibrin plug formation at the site of rupture. These spots are associated with infective endocarditis and are thought to result from immune complex deposition or microemboli. They are a characteristic ocular finding in infective endocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJaneway lesions\u003C/strong\u003E are non-tender, erythematous or haemorrhagic macules on the palms and soles, caused by septic microemboli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsler nodes\u003C/strong\u003E are painful, raised lesions found on the pads of fingers and toes, caused by immune complex deposition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplinter haemorrhages\u003C/strong\u003E are linear dark streaks under the nails, caused by microemboli to small vessels in the nail bed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPetechiae\u003C/strong\u003E are small, round, purplish spots on the skin or mucous membranes, caused by minor haemorrhages from small blood vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile all these manifestations can be seen in infective endocarditis, only Roth spots specifically involve retinal vessel rupture and fibrin plug formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Roth spots are retinal haemorrhages with pale centres, caused by rupture of retinal vessels and fibrin plug formation in infective endocarditis."],"references":["Ashley EA, Niebauer J. Cardiology Explained. London: Remedica; 2004. Chapter 10, Infective endocarditis. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK2208/","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. Robbins Basic Pathology (10th ed.). 2017. Elsevier - Health Sciences Division","Beaulieu A, Rehman HU. Janeway lesions. CMAJ. 2010 Jul 13;182(10):1075. doi: 10.1503/cmaj.091528. Epub 2010 May 10. PMID: 20457771; PMCID: PMC2900332."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45665"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14453"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45665"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T13:25:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T13:25:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7148"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60245"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identif